RECORD: don't assert when there are no record contexts (malloc(0) -> NULL on Phoenix)

RecordAClientStateChange() handles a client disconnecting (ClientStateGone /
ClientStateRetained) by snapshotting the global ppAllContexts array so it can
walk it while RecordDisableContext() mutates the original. It allocates that
copy unconditionally and asserts the result is non-NULL:

    numContextsCopy = numContexts;
    ppAllContextsCopy = xallocarray(numContextsCopy, sizeof(RecordContextPtr));
    assert(ppAllContextsCopy);

When no record context is active numContexts == 0, so xallocarray(0, ...) calls
malloc(0). On Phoenix-RTOS (and any conforming C library that may return NULL
for a zero-size request) that yields NULL, the assert fires and the server
aborts with SIGABRT. This is exactly what happens under Window Maker: it is the
first client whose disconnect/state-change drives the RECORD ClientStateCallback
while no recording client is attached (xtrace etc. never run), so twm/jwm/xeyes
/xterm never hit it.

There is nothing to snapshot or notify when there are no contexts, so return
early. The assert is kept for the real allocation-failure case (numContexts > 0).
This is a genuine malloc(0)-returns-NULL portability fix, upstreamable as-is.

--- a/record/record.c
+++ b/record/record.c
@@ -2728,6 +2728,8 @@ RecordAClientStateChange(CallbackListPtr *pcbl, void *nulldata,

         /* RecordDisableContext modifies contents of ppAllContexts. */
         numContextsCopy = numContexts;
+        if (numContextsCopy == 0)
+            break;
         ppAllContextsCopy = xallocarray(numContextsCopy,
                                         sizeof(RecordContextPtr));
         assert(ppAllContextsCopy);
